       However, with all this joy to be had, I am extremely sad. I have had around two to three hours of gameplay in Zelda. The gamecube I own is roughly a year and a half old. When I get to the top of the Dragon's roost, I pull a &quot;Cannot read Disk error&quot; every time I enter new area's. I have cleaned the lense, the game, checked the disks, and checked the other disks. It seems the problem lies within the cube, and most likely with the lense. Sending it to be fixed is $75, and I don't want to buy a new one because I have this suspiscion that that's exactly what Nintendo wants. Perhaps they planned the cube to break down within two years (exceeding warrenty), and made it a pain in the ass to fix. All I know, is I can't play a wonderful game, and will have to pay out the ass to play the thing. Woe is me.<br>
